(-Potentials of Casein Micelles from Reconstituted Skim Milk Heated at 120℃
Skelte G. Anemaab* & Henning Klostermeyerª ªForschungszentrum für Milch und Lebensmittel Weihenstephan, Technische Universität München, D85350 Freising, Germany bPresent address: Food Science Section, New Zealand Dairy Research Institute, Private Bag 11029, Palmerston, North New Zealand (Received 20 January 1995; accepted 21 October 1995)
ABSTRACT
Laser Doppler electrophoresis was used to determine the (-potentials of casein micelles in untreated, rennet treated or heated (pH 6.6 or 7.1|120℃ for 6, 15 or 25 min) reconstituted skim milk samples as a function of pH. Complex (-poten- tial-pH profiles were observed for untreated milk samples, with local maxima at pH 5.0 and 6.5 and corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. Rennet treatment of milk reduced the micellar (-potential by approximately one-third. On heat treat- ment of the milk, the maxima and minima were either markedly reduced or elimi- nated. In addition, the casein micelles from the samples heated at pH 6.6 had higher (-potentials than those from the samples heated at pH 7.1 over the entire pH range. Low levels of K-casein were dissociated from the casein micelles on heat treatment at pH 6.6, whereas about 50% of the K-casein was rendered soluble on heat treatment at pH 7.1. This dissociation of K-casein, which was partially reversible on readjustment of the pH, may account for the observed differences in micellar (-potential between milk samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1. INTRODUCTION
The caseins of bovine milk are in the form of colloidal aggregates called micelles. Although the detailed structure of the casein micelle has not been unequivocally elucidated, several models have been proposed (Rose, 1969; Waugh, 1971; Slat- tery & Evard, 1973; Schmidt, 1980, 1982; Horne et al., 1989; Holt, 1992). models have been progressively refined as more information on the micelle structure has become available. Most of the experimental data to date can be explained by a porous structure composed of small units, the sub-micelles, which are held together by colloidal calcium phosphate (CCP). K-Casein is not spread uniformly through the micelle, but occupies a key position at the micelle surface (Kirchmeier, 1973; Schmidt, 1982; Walstra & Jenness, 1984; Walstra, 1990). Recently, Holt (1992) has proposed a structural representation of the casein micelle that departs from the current theory of defined sub-micelles, as the micelle sub-structure in this model consists of the caseins in a mineralised cross-linked protein gel arising from short range, but not long range order.
The casein micelle constitutes a colloidal system of remarkable stability, capable of withstanding the severe treatments that are commonly associated with the modern commercial processing of milk and dairy products. In most cases, hydrophobic colloids are stabilised by electrostatic repulsive forces between elec- trical double layers of the particles and the long range van der Waals' attractive forces, as has been described by the classical Deryagin-Landau-Verwey-Over- beek or DLVO theory (Verwey & Overbeek, 1948). There have been many attempts to use the DLVO theory to describe the stability of casein micelles (Green & Crutchfield, 1971; Green, 1973; Pearce, 1976); however, the limitations of this approach have been discussed by Payens (1979) and Schmidt (1982).
The importance of K-casein in maintaining casein micelle stability has been recognised for a long time. This protein is thought to be associated with the micelles in such a way that the hydrophilic negatively-charged macropeptide region projects into the solvent as flexible hairs (Walstra, 1979, 1990; Walstra & Jenness, 1984). A surface layer of this type would provide stabilisation through electrostatic repulsion between the charged casein micelles as in the DLVO mechanism, as well as steric stabilisation through entropic repulsions at close range due to the presence of the macropeptide hairs (Walstra, 1990).
The surface charge of colloids is often estimated by the (-potential which can be derived from the electrophoretic mobility of the particles. However, the quantitative calculation of (-potentials from electrophoretic mobilities for casein micelles is complicated by the fact that the nature of the electrical double layer is unknown, the micelle surface is diffuse and the micelle structure is porous and highly hydrated (Payens, 1979). Despite this limitation, the measurement of (- potentials should yield information on the nature of the outer (shear) layer of the casein micelle as changes in the chemical or physical characteristics of this surface during the treatment of milk should be apparent from the changes to the elec- trophoretic mobility and therefore the (-potential.
The electrophoretic mobility and (-potential of natural and rennet-treated casein micelles under a variety of conditions have been reported (Green & Crutchfield, 1971; Pearce, 1976; Darling & Dickson, 1979a, b; Dalgleish, 1984). In all cases, the action of rennet reduced the {-potential of the micelles to about half of the original value. The marked reduction in the (-potential on the rennet treatment of casein micelles led Green & Crutchfield (1971) to the conclusion that casein micelle stability was entirely a consequence of electrostatic repulsions; however, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Payens (1979) suggested that the magnitude of the (-potential as well as some important stability characteristics of both native and rennet-treated casein micelles were not consistent with a colloidal system stabilised by electrostatic interactions alone.

Numerous reactions occur when milk is heated and many are likely to have an influence on the micellar (- potential (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988; Singh & Fox, 1988; Singh & Creamer, 1992). In contrast to what may be expected, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) reported negligible changes to the (-potential of casein micelles on heating milk to the coagulation point. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed a complex relationship between the (-potential and pH for casein micelles heated in the presence of whey proteins; however, these effects could not be related to changes in the corresponding heat stability curves.
This communication reports the results of a study on the effect of the heat treatment of skim milk reconstituted to 10 and 25% total solids (TS) on the electrophoretic mobility and thereby the calculated (-potential of casein micelles. The {-potentials of micelles from untreated and rennet-treated milk samples were compared.
MATERIALS AND METHODS
Milk supply
Reconstituted skim milk was used in all experiments as this avoided variations in milk supply and allowed milk of the required total solids to be prepared. Experi- mental reconstituted skim milk samples of 10 and 25% TS were prepared by mixing the appropriate quantity of low heat skim milk powder (whey protein nitrogen index >6; Sanderson, 1970) with purified water and allowing the mixture to equilibrate at ambient temperature (approximately 20℃) for 2 h.
Dissociation and reassociation behaviour of K-casein
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk
Milk samples (10% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1 by the slow addition of 1 M HCI or 1 M NaOH to well-stirred solutions. Sub-samples (6 mL) in glass tubes were heated at 120°℃ for 6 min in a thermostatically-controlled oil bath, then cooled by immersion into cold water. After heat treatment, the pH was readjusted to values in the range 5.0 to 8.0 with 1 M HCI or 1 M NaOH and the samples were equilibrated for 2 h.
Ultracentrifugation and gel electrophoresis
The heated, pH-adjusted milk samples were centrifuged at 88,000 g for 60 min at 25°C in a Beckman L8-80M ultracentrifuge and the associated nVT90 rotor (Beckman Instruments Inc., Palo Alto, CA, USA). The protein components in the ultracentrifugal supernatants were separated and identified by sodium dode- cyl sulphate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE), using the mini Protean II equipment (Bio-Rad Laboratories, Richmond, CA, USA) and an experimental method similar to that described by Laemmli (1970). After staining (Coomassie Blue R250) and destaining procedures, the band intensities of the major protein components were determined using a Molecular Dynamics Model P.D. Computing Densitometer (Molecular Dynamics, Sunnyvale, CA, USA) and the associated Imagequant integration software.

Measurement of (-potential and particle size
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk
Milk samples (10 and 25% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1, heated and cooled as described above. For the final experiments, heating times of 25 min (10% TS samples) or 15 min (25% TS samples) were used. The concentrated milk sample at pH 7.1, which had partially coagulated on heat treatment, was centrifuged at 3000 rev/min in a bench centrifuge (Sigma 3E) to remove the small amount of coagulated material and the supernatant milk sample was used for (-potential measurements.
Rennet treatment of milk
Rennet solution was prepared by dissolving 0.25 g rennet powder (Hauser rennet powder, Josef Hauser, Ottmaishausen, Germany) in 50 mL water before filtration through a 0.1 um pore size cellulose nitrate filter. Freshly prepared rennet solu- tion was added to 10% TS skim milk at room temperature.
Buffers
Synthetic milk ultrafiltrate (SMUF buffer) was prepared by the method of Jenness & Koops (1962). Immediately prior to use, samples of the SMUF buffer were adjusted to pH 4.75 to 8.0 using 1 M HCI or 1 M KOH. Ca2+-imidazole buffer was prepared from 20 mM imidazole, 50 mM NaCl and 5 mM CaCl2. The pH was adjusted to 6.0 to 7.5 by the addition of 1 M HC1. All buffers were filtered through 0.25 um pore size cellulose nitrate filters before use.
Electrophoretic mobility and (-potential determination
The electrophoretic mobilities and hence the calculated (-potentials of casein micelles were determined using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 instrument, the associated Malvern Multi-8 64 channel correlator and the AZ4 standard electrophoresis cell which incorporates a 4 mm diameter quartz capillary (Malvern Instruments Ltd, Malvern, Worcs., UK). The temperature of the electrophoresis cell was maintained at 30°℃ by a water jacket which was temperature controlled by the Peltier system associated with the electrophoresis cell. Monitoring of temperature indicated that control was better than +0.5℃. An applied voltage of 80 V (corresponding to a sensed voltage of approximately 60 V across the capillary, i.e. approximately 12 V/ cm) and a modulation frequency of 250 Hz were used in all experiments.
The SMUF and Ca2+-imidazole buffers were highly conducting, which resul- ted in sample heating if voltages were applied for long periods. This was over- come by using duty cycle mode in which the voltage was switched off for short periods between each voltage pulse to allow generated heat to dissipate. A duty cycle of 60% (a voltage pulse of 30 ms followed by an off-time of 20 ms) was used in all experiments. Electrode polarisation was avoided by reversing the direction of the applied field every 2 Hz.
Samples for {-potential measurement were prepared by suspending typically 50 uL of 10% TS milk or 20 uL of 25% TS milk in 15 mL of the appropriate buffer; however, for buffers in the pH range 5.25 to 6.0, higher milk concentrations, up to 200 AL of 10% TS milk in 15 mL of buffer, were required to give samples that were sufficiently turbid. Milk samples dispersed in the appropriate buffer were allowed to equilibrate for 15 min before (-potential determination. Each sample was measured in triplicate. Casein micelle size measurements
Particle sizes in untreated and heated milk (10% TS samples at pH 6.6 or 7.1 only) were measured in suspensions by adding 25 uL of milk to 15 mL of Ca2+_ imidazole buffer at pH 7.0. Measurements of the average diameters were made using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 in photon correlation mode, with the correlation functions measured at a scattering angle of 90° only. The correlation functions were analysed by the method of cumulants to give average diffusion coefficients from which the average hydrodynamic diameters and polydispersity of the parti- cles were calculated using Stokes' law. Each sample was measured five times and the average size and polydispersity determined.
All experiments reported above were repeated on at least two occasions with similar results.

The electrophoretic mobility is determined from the magnitude of the Doppler shift in the laser radiation that is scattered from the charged particles moving in a defined electric field. The calculated ¿- potentials of casein micelles from unheated milk samples dispersed in SMUF buffer and filtered through 0.8 um pore size filters were, within error, indistinguishable from those of unfiltered samples. Dalgleish (1984) reported that, if fresh milk was skimmed by centrifugation and no other measures were taken to remove fat, two peaks corresponding to the (-potentials of casein micelles and fat globules were observed. It is possible that in these experiments, where reconstituted skim milk was used, the fat globules remaining in the skim milk powder were well homogenised so that casein micelle material formed a synthetic fat globule membrane. Dalgleish (1984) established that particles from homo- genised milk had (-potentials very similar to those of native casein micelles. All further (-potential determinations were on unfiltered milk suspensions as it was possible that filtration may remove some of the larger particles formed during the heat treatment of milk and therefore influence the calculated ¿- potential. Particles from heated milk samples also tended to adsorb to the cellulose nitrate filters which made the preparation of suitably concentrated suspensions difficult.
Comparison of ¿- potentials of casein micelles from untreated and rennet-treated skim milk
The (-potentials for native casein micelles, measured in SMUF buffer, ranged from about -20 to -13 mV over the pH range 8.0 to 4.75 (Fig. 1). The relation- ship between pH and (-potential for casein micelles showed local maxima at pH 5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. When Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used as the suspending medium, the calculated (-potentials were markedly lower than the values found when using SMUF buffer (Fig. 1).
The rennet treatment of the milk reduced the (-potential of the casein micelles to about two-thirds of the original value in both buffer systems. As with the native casein micelles, the apparent (-potentials were markedly lower when the Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used instead of the SMUF buffer (Fig. 1). Rennet solution was added to milk at low concentration so that the enzymatic reaction lasted for about 100 min. To avoid the formation of large particles, which can cause problems with anomalous light scattering, the rennet-treated milk was dispersed in the buffers before the completion of the enzymatic reaction (i.e. after about 50 min).
The (-potentials of casein micelles from heat-treated skim milk
The (-potential-pH profiles for casein micelles from the heated skim milk samples, in comparison with unheated milk, are shown in Fig. 2. In SMUF buffer, the maximum and minimum observed at low pH for the unheated milk were absent for the heated 10% TS milk samples and were considerably less pronounced in the profiles for the heated 25% TS milk samples. The maximum and minimum observed at high pH in the unheated milk were less pronounced in the samples heated at pH 6.6.
For both the 10 and 25% TS milk concentrations at any particular pH, the (- potentials of the micelles from the milk samples heated at pH 6.6 were higher than those for the corresponding samples heated at pH 7.1 in both buffer systems.

Particle size of casein micelles from untreated and heat-treated skim milk
The average hydrodynamic radius and polydispersity of the casein micelles from unheated and heat-treated 10% TS skim milk samples are given in Table 1. In the milk samples which were initially at pH 7.1, a very small increase in average diameter was observed on heat treatment for 6 min. Extending the heating time to 25 min resulted in a marked increase in the average diameter of the particles to sizes similar to those observed for the samples heated for 25 min at pH 6.6.

The (-potentials were also similar to those obtained by Dalgleish (1984), although markedly higher than the results Banon & Hardy (1992); these latter two studies also used laser Doppler electrophoresis techniques. The (-potential values for casein micelles reported here were almost twice as high as those determined by electro- osmosis techniques (Payens, 1966; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).
The marked reduction in micellar (-potential when the suspending medium was changed from SMUF to Ca2+-imidazole buffer (Fig. 1 and Fig. 2) may have been a reflection of the difference in Ca2+ activity between the two buffer systems, although factors such as differences in buffer viscosity or the presence of ions such as phosphate may have also contributed to this disparity. Both Pearce (1976) and Dalgleish (1984) showed that increasing Ca2+ concentration caused a considerable decrease in the (-potential of native and rennet-treated casein micelles.
Considering only the protein part of casein micelles, a steady increase in (- potential with increasing pH would be expected (Shaw, 1980). However, the observed relationship between the (-potential of native casein micelles from milk dispersed in SMUF buffer and pH is considerably more complex, as local maxima were observed at pH 5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5 (Fig. 1). Overall, the (-potential-pH profile shown in Fig. 1 is similar to that reported by Schmidt & Poll (1986) for casein micelles heated in the absence of whey proteins; however, the entire curve is transposed by about 10 mV to higher (-potential. In addition, Schmidt & Poll (1986) did not observe the maxi- mum at pH 6.5 and the minimum at pH 7.5 unless whey proteins were present during heating of the casein micelles. Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Banon & Hardy (1992) reported an almost linear decrease in the (-potential of casein micelles with decreasing pH when milk ultrafiltrate was used as the dispersion medium.
The complete solubilisation of CCP at pH 5.3 (Van Hooydonk et al., 1986; Dalgleish & Law, 1989) may be responsible for the maximum and minimum in the (-potential-pH profile at pH 5.0 and 5.5, respectively (Walstra, 1990). Alter- natively, these extremes may arise from changes in the surface charge character- istics of the casein micelle as a consequence of the increased adsorption of ionic calcium to protein-bound phosphate groups at pH in the range 5.3 to 5.6 (Crea- mer, 1985; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).
As no (-potential maximum at pH 6.5 or minimum at pH 7.5 were observed when Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used, these may be a consequence of pH- dependent changes in the properties of the SMUF buffer. The addition of milk to SMUF buffer during sample preparation partially inhibited the precipitation of calcium phosphate from these buffers at high pH (>7.0). This indicated that the calcium phosphate may preferentially adsorb to the casein micelles. This asso- ciation may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential, and hence account for the minimum at pH 7.5.
The (-potential at pH 4.75 was markedly higher than zero (Fig. 1). This contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Schmidt & Poll (1986) who reported a (-potential of zero at the isoelectric pH of casein (pH 4.6). The heat treatment of milk at high temperatures results in many physical and chemical changes to the milk system that may influence the casein micelle (- potential. These changes include precipitation of calcium phosphate, depho- sphorylation of casein, association of heat-denatured whey proteins with the casein micelles and the dissociation of micellar casein (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988; Singh & Creamer, 1992). The results shown in Fig. 2 demonstrate that heat treatment of the skim milk affected the (-potential-pH profile of the casein micelles. In all cases, the {-potentials of the casein micelles from the milk samples heated at pH 6.6 were higher than in samples adjusted to pH 7.1, although the differences were small at pH below 6.0 due to the convergence of the curves at low pH. This contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) who reported no significant effect of the heat treatment of milk up to the coagulation point. The comparison is complicated by the fact that they heated milk samples only at pH close to that naturally observed and did not take the pH change incurred by heating into account. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed that the heat treatment of casein micelle dispersions in the presence of whey proteins increased the (-potential in the pH range 6.6 to 6.9 but reduced it at higher pH.
The particle size results given in Table 1 demonstrate that differences in micelle size as a consequence of the heat treatments of 10% TS milk samples could not account for the observed differences in (-potential between pH 6.6 and 7.1. It should be noted that the electrophoretic mobility, and therefore the derived (- potentials of non-conducting particles, as derived from the Smoluchowski equa- tion, should be independent of their size and shape (Shaw, 1980).
On heating milk (>90℃), a pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the casein micelles occurs (Kudo, 1980; Singh & Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer, 1991; Anema et al., 1993). Little K-casein dissociates from the micelles on heat treatment of unconcentrated milk at pH lower than maximum heat stability (pH <6.7). Above pH 6.7, a high proportion of the x-casein, complexed with dena- tured whey proteins, is dissociated from the casein micelles. As the milk solids concentration is increased, the heat-induced dissociation of K-casein occurs at progressively lower pH and the extent of dissociation increases (Singh & Crea- mer, 1991; Anema et al., 1993).
Singh & Fox (1985, 1986) proposed that, as K-casein is the major stabilising component of the casein micelles, the minimum in the HCT-pH profile for unconcentrated milk (Rose, 1961) results from the premature coagulation of the K-casein-depleted casein micelles through calcium-mediated aggregation reac- tions. Although K-casein dissociation increases at higher pH, the heat stability increases again due to the increase in protein charge which is sufficient to offset the destabilisation effects of K-casein depletion. Similarly, Singh & Creamer (1991) suggested that the low heat stability of concentrated milk over a wide pH range (6.3-7.3) is due to the increased dissociation of K-casein at lower pH. The heat coagulation process of concentrated milk is therefore comparable with that existing for unconcentrated milk in the region of minimum heat stability and several pieces of experimental evidence support this view (Muir & Sweetsur, 1978; Singh & Creamer, 1992).
The present study clearly indicated that the K-casein-depleted micelles, formed

when milk was heated at pH 7.1, had a lower (-potential than the whey-protein- coated micelles formed when milk was heated at pH 6.6. In concurrence with earlier reports, the minima in the HCT-pH profile of unconcentrated milk and the low stability of concentrated milk throughout the pH range could be explained as being a consequence of the reduction in ¿- potential and steric stabi- lisation due to the pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the micelles (Singh & Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer, 1991). Alternatively, the reduction in (- potential may arise from an increase in the heat-induced precipitation of calcium phosphate at higher milk pH. An association of this calcium phosphate with casein may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential. Surprisingly, the (-potentials did not markedly increase at pH higher than that where the minimum heat stability of milk occurs. Unless this situation is different at high temperatures, the increase in heat stability of unconcentrated milk at pH above 7.0 cannot be explained by an increase in the surface charge of the micelles. As the direct cause of coagulation of the K-casein-depleted micelles is considered to be their increased sensitivity to precipitation by calcium, the increase in stabi- lity at higher pH may simply be a result of the reduced availability of ionic calcium.
The results shown in Fig. 3 indicate that the heat-induced dissociation of micellar K-casein is partially reversible on pH readjustment after heat treatment. For the sample heated at pH 6.6, little soluble casein was noted and virtually no effect was observed on readjusting the pH after heat treatment. In contrast, for the samples heated at pH 7.1, the dissociated K-casein partially reassociated with the casein micelles when the pH was lowered, with the degree of reassociation increasing at lower pH. In addition, the level of dissociated K-casein increased if the pH after heat treatment was raised. These results suggest that the convergence of the (-potential-pH curves for the samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1 may be a consequence of the reassociation of K-casein with the casein micelles when the pH is lowered after heat treatment. As the solubility of calcium phosphate salts increases with a reduction in pH, the convergence of the two curves could also be explained by the resolubilisation of heat-precipitated calcium phosphate as the pH of the system is reduced.
CONCLUSIONS
This study has demonstrated that the changes in (-potential in heated skim milk are consistent with the present theory for the pH-dependence of the heat stability of skim milk. Casein micelles from milk samples heated at pH 7.1 had lower č- potentials than those from milk samples heated at pH 6.6. The (-potential of the casein micelles did not increase at pH above 7 suggesting that the increase in the heat stability of unconcentrated skim milk at these high pH values may be a consequence of the decrease in calcium ion concentration rather than an increase in protein charge. However, the reduced (-potentials could also be explained by increased precipitation of calcium phosphate at higher pH.
A major limitation in studying the changes to casein micelles on heat treatment is that, with the current technology, it is not possible to measure the (-potential at the temperature of heating. ABSTRACT
Laser Doppler electrophoresis was used to determine the (-potentials of casein
micelles in untreated, rennet treated or heated (pH 6.6 or 7.1|120℃ for 6, 15 or
25 min) reconstituted skim milk samples as a function of pH. Complex (-poten-
tial-pH profiles were observed for untreated milk samples, with local maxima at
pH 5.0 and 6.5 and corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. Rennet treatment of
milk reduced the micellar (-potential by approximately one-third. On heat treat-
ment of the milk, the maxima and minima were either markedly reduced or elimi-
nated. In addition, the casein micelles from the samples heated at pH 6.6 had
higher (-potentials than those from the samples heated at pH 7.1 over the entire
pH range. Low levels of K-casein were dissociated from the casein micelles on heat
treatment at pH 6.6, whereas about 50% of the K-casein was rendered soluble on
heat treatment at pH 7.1. This dissociation of K-casein, which was partially
reversible on readjustment of the pH, may account for the observed differences in
micellar (-potential between milk samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1. Copyright C
1996 Elsevier Science Limited
INTRODUCTION
The caseins of bovine milk are in the form of colloidal aggregates called micelles.
Although the detailed structure of the casein micelle has not been unequivocally
elucidated, several models have been proposed (Rose, 1969; Waugh, 1971; Slat-
tery & Evard, 1973; Schmidt, 1980, 1982; Horne et al., 1989; Holt, 1992). These
*To whom correspondence should be addressed.
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer
models have been progressively refined as more information on the micelle
structure has become available. Most of the experimental data to date can be
explained by a porous structure composed of small units, the sub-micelles, which
are held together by colloidal calcium phosphate (CCP). K-Casein is not spread
uniformly through the micelle, but occupies a key position at the micelle surface
(Kirchmeier, 1973; Schmidt, 1982; Walstra & Jenness, 1984; Walstra, 1990).
Recently, Holt (1992) has proposed a structural representation of the casein
micelle that departs from the current theory of defined sub-micelles, as the micelle
sub-structure in this model consists of the caseins in a mineralised cross-linked
protein gel arising from short range, but not long range order.
The casein micelle constitutes a colloidal system of remarkable stability,
capable of withstanding the severe treatments that are commonly associated with
the modern commercial processing of milk and dairy products. In most cases,
hydrophobic colloids are stabilised by electrostatic repulsive forces between elec-
trical double layers of the particles and the long range van der Waals' attractive
forces, as has been described by the classical Deryagin-Landau-Verwey-Over-
beek or DLVO theory (Verwey & Overbeek, 1948). There have been many
attempts to use the DLVO theory to describe the stability of casein micelles
(Green & Crutchfield, 1971; Green, 1973; Pearce, 1976); however, the limitations
of this approach have been discussed by Payens (1979) and Schmidt (1982).
The importance of K-casein in maintaining casein micelle stability has been
recognised for a long time. This protein is thought to be associated with the
micelles in such a way that the hydrophilic negatively-charged macropeptide
region projects into the solvent as flexible hairs (Walstra, 1979, 1990; Walstra &
Jenness, 1984). A surface layer of this type would provide stabilisation through
electrostatic repulsion between the charged casein micelles as in the DLVO
mechanism, as well as steric stabilisation through entropic repulsions at close
range due to the presence of the macropeptide hairs (Walstra, 1990).
The surface charge of colloids is often estimated by the (-potential which can
be derived from the electrophoretic mobility of the particles. However, the
quantitative calculation of (-potentials from electrophoretic mobilities for casein
micelles is complicated by the fact that the nature of the electrical double layer is
unknown, the micelle surface is diffuse and the micelle structure is porous and
highly hydrated (Payens, 1979). Despite this limitation, the measurement of (-
potentials should yield information on the nature of the outer (shear) layer of the
casein micelle as changes in the chemical or physical characteristics of this surface
during the treatment of milk should be apparent from the changes to the elec-
trophoretic mobility and therefore the (-potential.
The electrophoretic mobility and (-potential of natural and rennet-treated
casein micelles under a variety of conditions have been reported (Green &
Crutchfield, 1971; Pearce, 1976; Darling & Dickson, 1979a, b; Dalgleish, 1984).
In all cases, the action of rennet reduced the {-potential of the micelles to about
half of the original value. The marked reduction in the (-potential on the rennet
treatment of casein micelles led Green & Crutchfield (1971) to the conclusion that
casein micelle stability was entirely a consequence of electrostatic repulsions;
however, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Payens (1979) suggested that the
magnitude of the (-potential as well as some important stability characteristics of
both native and rennet-treated casein micelles were not consistent with a colloidal
system stabilised by electrostatic interactions alone.
In contrast to the numerous studies on the changes in (-potential between
(-Potentials of casein micelles from heated skim milk
native and rennet-treated casein micelles, the effect of heat treatment on the (-
potential of the micelles has received little attention. Numerous reactions occur
when milk is heated and many are likely to have an influence on the micellar (-
potential (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988; Singh & Fox, 1988; Singh & Creamer, 1992).
In contrast to what may be expected, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) reported
negligible changes to the (-potential of casein micelles on heating milk to the
coagulation point. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed a complex relationship between
the (-potential and pH for casein micelles heated in the presence of whey proteins;
however, these effects could not be related to changes in the corresponding heat
stability curves.
This communication reports the results of a study on the effect of the heat
treatment of skim milk reconstituted to 10 and 25% total solids (TS) on the
electrophoretic mobility and thereby the calculated (-potential of casein micelles.
The {-potentials of micelles from untreated and rennet-treated milk samples were
compared.
MATERIALS AND METHODS
Milk supply
Reconstituted skim milk was used in all experiments as this avoided variations in
milk supply and allowed milk of the required total solids to be prepared. Experi-
mental reconstituted skim milk samples of 10 and 25% TS were prepared by
mixing the appropriate quantity of low heat skim milk powder (whey protein
nitrogen index >6; Sanderson, 1970) with purified water and allowing the
mixture to equilibrate at ambient temperature (approximately 20℃) for 2 h.
Dissociation and reassociation behaviour of K-casein
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk
Milk samples (10% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1 by the slow addition of 1
M HCI or 1 M NaOH to well-stirred solutions. Sub-samples (6 mL) in glass tubes
were heated at 120°℃ for 6 min in a thermostatically-controlled oil bath, then
cooled by immersion into cold water. After heat treatment, the pH was readjusted
to values in the range 5.0 to 8.0 with 1 M HCI or 1 M NaOH and the samples were
equilibrated for 2 h.
Ultracentrifugation and gel electrophoresis
The heated, pH-adjusted milk samples were centrifuged at 88,000 g for 60 min at
25°C in a Beckman L8-80M ultracentrifuge and the associated nVT90 rotor
(Beckman Instruments Inc., Palo Alto, CA, USA). The protein components in
the ultracentrifugal supernatants were separated and identified by sodium dode-
cyl sulphate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE), using the mini
Protean II equipment (Bio-Rad Laboratories, Richmond, CA, USA) and an
experimental method similar to that described by Laemmli (1970). After staining
(Coomassie Blue R250) and destaining procedures, the band intensities of the
major protein components were determined using a Molecular Dynamics Model
P.D. Computing Densitometer (Molecular Dynamics, Sunnyvale, CA, USA) and
the associated Imagequant integration software.
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer
Measurement of (-potential and particle size
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk
Milk samples (10 and 25% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1, heated and cooled
as described above. For the final experiments, heating times of 25 min (10% TS
samples) or 15 min (25% TS samples) were used. The concentrated milk sample
at pH 7.1, which had partially coagulated on heat treatment, was centrifuged at
3000 rev/min in a bench centrifuge (Sigma 3E) to remove the small amount of
coagulated material and the supernatant milk sample was used for (-potential
measurements.
Rennet treatment of milk
Rennet solution was prepared by dissolving 0.25 g rennet powder (Hauser rennet
powder, Josef Hauser, Ottmaishausen, Germany) in 50 mL water before filtration
through a 0.1 um pore size cellulose nitrate filter. Freshly prepared rennet solu-
tion was added to 10% TS skim milk at room temperature.
Buffers
Synthetic milk ultrafiltrate (SMUF buffer) was prepared by the method of
Jenness & Koops (1962). Immediately prior to use, samples of the SMUF buffer
were adjusted to pH 4.75 to 8.0 using 1 M HCI or 1 M KOH. Ca2+-imidazole
buffer was prepared from 20 mM imidazole, 50 mM NaCl and 5 mM CaCl2. The
pH was adjusted to 6.0 to 7.5 by the addition of 1 M HC1. All buffers were filtered
through 0.25 um pore size cellulose nitrate filters before use.
Electrophoretic mobility and (-potential determination
The electrophoretic mobilities and hence the calculated (-potentials of casein
micelles were determined using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 instrument, the associated
Malvern Multi-8 64 channel correlator and the AZ4 standard electrophoresis cell
which incorporates a 4 mm diameter quartz capillary (Malvern Instruments Ltd,
Malvern, Worcs., UK). The temperature of the electrophoresis cell was maintained
at 30°℃ by a water jacket which was temperature controlled by the Peltier system
associated with the electrophoresis cell. Monitoring of temperature indicated that
control was better than +0.5℃. An applied voltage of 80 V (corresponding to a
sensed voltage of approximately 60 V across the capillary, i.e. approximately 12 V/
cm) and a modulation frequency of 250 Hz were used in all experiments.
The SMUF and Ca2+-imidazole buffers were highly conducting, which resul-
ted in sample heating if voltages were applied for long periods. This was over-
come by using duty cycle mode in which the voltage was switched off for short
periods between each voltage pulse to allow generated heat to dissipate. A duty
cycle of 60% (a voltage pulse of 30 ms followed by an off-time of 20 ms) was used
in all experiments. Electrode polarisation was avoided by reversing the direction
of the applied field every 2 Hz.
Samples for {-potential measurement were prepared by suspending typically 50
uL of 10% TS milk or 20 uL of 25% TS milk in 15 mL of the appropriate buffer;
however, for buffers in the pH range 5.25 to 6.0, higher milk concentrations, up to
200 AL of 10% TS milk in 15 mL of buffer, were required to give samples that were
sufficiently turbid. Milk samples dispersed in the appropriate buffer were allowed to
equilibrate for 15 min before (-potential determination. Each sample was measured
in triplicate. The error in the (-potential determinations, determined by repeatedly
(-Potentials of casein micelles from heated skim milk
measuring the (-potential of unheated casein micelles in SMUF or Ca2+-imidazole
buffer, was found to be consistently better than +0.5 mV.
Casein micelle size measurements
Particle sizes in untreated and heated milk (10% TS samples at pH 6.6 or 7.1
only) were measured in suspensions by adding 25 uL of milk to 15 mL of Ca2+_
imidazole buffer at pH 7.0. Measurements of the average diameters were made
using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 in photon correlation mode, with the correlation
functions measured at a scattering angle of 90° only. The correlation functions
were analysed by the method of cumulants to give average diffusion coefficients
from which the average hydrodynamic diameters and polydispersity of the parti-
cles were calculated using Stokes' law. Each sample was measured five times and
the average size and polydispersity determined.
All experiments reported above were repeated on at least two occasions with
similar results.
Theory of laser Doppler electrophoresis technique for (-potential determination
The design and principles of laser Doppler electrophoresis have been described in
detail by Ware & Flygare (1972). The electrophoretic mobility is determined from
the magnitude of the Doppler shift in the laser radiation that is scattered from the
charged particles moving in a defined electric field. The (-potential can be deter-
mined from the electrophoretic mobility (uE) using the equation of Henry (1931);

The viscosity and dielectric constant were taken to be those of water, and the

RESULTS
Although this paper describes changes in (-potentials of casein micelles, it must
be remembered that these are calculated from the electrophoretic mobility of the
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer
micelles, which is the variable that was actually measured. As the surface charges
of casein micelles are negative, the (-potential is also negative. The changes
reported refer to the absolute magnitude of the (-potential.
The calculated ¿- potentials of casein micelles from unheated milk samples
dispersed in SMUF buffer and filtered through 0.8 um pore size filters were, within
error, indistinguishable from those of unfiltered samples. Dalgleish (1984) reported
that, if fresh milk was skimmed by centrifugation and no other measures were
taken to remove fat, two peaks corresponding to the (-potentials of casein micelles
and fat globules were observed. It is possible that in these experiments, where
reconstituted skim milk was used, the fat globules remaining in the skim milk
powder were well homogenised so that casein micelle material formed a synthetic
fat globule membrane. Dalgleish (1984) established that particles from homo-
genised milk had (-potentials very similar to those of native casein micelles. All
further (-potential determinations were on unfiltered milk suspensions as it was
possible that filtration may remove some of the larger particles formed during the
heat treatment of milk and therefore influence the calculated ¿- potential. Particles
from heated milk samples also tended to adsorb to the cellulose nitrate filters which
made the preparation of suitably concentrated suspensions difficult.
Comparison of ¿- potentials of casein micelles from untreated and rennet-treated
skim milk
The (-potentials for native casein micelles, measured in SMUF buffer, ranged
from about -20 to -13 mV over the pH range 8.0 to 4.75 (Fig. 1). The relation-
ship between pH and (-potential for casein micelles showed local maxima at pH
5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. When Ca2+-imidazole
buffer was used as the suspending medium, the calculated (-potentials were

The rennet treatment of the milk reduced the (-potential of the casein micelles

native casein micelles, the apparent (-potentials were markedly lower when the

lasted for about 100 min. To avoid the formation of large particles, which can
cause problems with anomalous light scattering, the rennet-treated milk was
dispersed in the buffers before the completion of the enzymatic reaction (i.e. after

The (-potentials of casein micelles from heat-treated skim milk

For both the 10 and 25% TS milk concentrations at any particular pH, the (-

than those for the corresponding samples heated at pH 7.1 in both buffer systems.

native and rennet-treated casein micelles (Fig. 1) comparable with those obtained
using conventional moving boundary electrophoresis techniques (Green &
Crutchfield, 1971; Pearce, 1976; Darling & Dickson, 1979a, b). The (-potentials
were also similar to those obtained by Dalgleish (1984), although markedly
higher than the results Banon & Hardy (1992); these latter two studies also used
laser Doppler electrophoresis techniques. The (-potential values for casein
micelles reported here were almost twice as high as those determined by electro-
osmosis techniques (Payens, 1966; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).
The marked reduction in micellar (-potential when the suspending medium was
changed from SMUF to Ca2+-imidazole buffer (Fig. 1 and Fig. 2) may have
been a reflection of the difference in Ca2+ activity between the two buffer
systems, although factors such as differences in buffer viscosity or the presence of
ions such as phosphate may have also contributed to this disparity. Both Pearce
(1976) and Dalgleish (1984) showed that increasing Ca2+ concentration caused a
considerable decrease in the (-potential of native and rennet-treated casein
micelles.
Considering only the protein part of casein micelles, a steady increase in (-
potential with increasing pH would be expected (Shaw, 1980). However, the
observed relationship between the (-potential of native casein micelles from milk
dispersed in SMUF buffer and pH is considerably more complex, as local
maxima were observed at pH 5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5
and 7.5 (Fig. 1). Overall, the (-potential-pH profile shown in Fig. 1 is similar to
that reported by Schmidt & Poll (1986) for casein micelles heated in the absence
of whey proteins; however, the entire curve is transposed by about 10 mV to
higher (-potential. In addition, Schmidt & Poll (1986) did not observe the maxi-
mum at pH 6.5 and the minimum at pH 7.5 unless whey proteins were present
during heating of the casein micelles. Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Banon &
Hardy (1992) reported an almost linear decrease in the (-potential of casein
micelles with decreasing pH when milk ultrafiltrate was used as the dispersion
medium.
The complete solubilisation of CCP at pH 5.3 (Van Hooydonk et al., 1986;
Dalgleish & Law, 1989) may be responsible for the maximum and minimum in
the (-potential-pH profile at pH 5.0 and 5.5, respectively (Walstra, 1990). Alter-
natively, these extremes may arise from changes in the surface charge character-
istics of the casein micelle as a consequence of the increased adsorption of ionic
calcium to protein-bound phosphate groups at pH in the range 5.3 to 5.6 (Crea-
mer, 1985; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).
As no (-potential maximum at pH 6.5 or minimum at pH 7.5 were observed
when Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used, these may be a consequence of pH-
dependent changes in the properties of the SMUF buffer. The addition of milk to
SMUF buffer during sample preparation partially inhibited the precipitation of
calcium phosphate from these buffers at high pH (>7.0). This indicated that the
calcium phosphate may preferentially adsorb to the casein micelles. This asso-
ciation may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential,
and hence account for the minimum at pH 7.5.
The (-potential at pH 4.75 was markedly higher than zero (Fig. 1). This
contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Schmidt & Poll
(1986) who reported a (-potential of zero at the isoelectric pH of casein (pH 4.6).
Due to the complete solubilisation of the CCP, the calcium and phosphate
concentrations, the calcium ion activity and the ionic strength of natural milk
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer
serum at pH 4.75 would be considerably higher than in the SMUF buffer used in
these experiments, which simulates milk serum at pH 6.6. It is possible that these
differences result in a higher -potential of the casein micelles in the SMUF buffer
systems at low pH.
The heat treatment of milk at high temperatures results in many physical and
chemical changes to the milk system that may influence the casein micelle (-
potential. These changes include precipitation of calcium phosphate, depho-
sphorylation of casein, association of heat-denatured whey proteins with the
casein micelles and the dissociation of micellar casein (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988;
Singh & Creamer, 1992). The results shown in Fig. 2 demonstrate that heat
treatment of the skim milk affected the (-potential-pH profile of the casein
micelles. In all cases, the {-potentials of the casein micelles from the milk samples
heated at pH 6.6 were higher than in samples adjusted to pH 7.1, although the
differences were small at pH below 6.0 due to the convergence of the curves at
low pH. This contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) who
reported no significant effect of the heat treatment of milk up to the coagulation
point. The comparison is complicated by the fact that they heated milk samples
only at pH close to that naturally observed and did not take the pH change
incurred by heating into account. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed that the heat
treatment of casein micelle dispersions in the presence of whey proteins increased
the (-potential in the pH range 6.6 to 6.9 but reduced it at higher pH.
The particle size results given in Table 1 demonstrate that differences in micelle
size as a consequence of the heat treatments of 10% TS milk samples could not
account for the observed differences in (-potential between pH 6.6 and 7.1. It
should be noted that the electrophoretic mobility, and therefore the derived (-
potentials of non-conducting particles, as derived from the Smoluchowski equa-
tion, should be independent of their size and shape (Shaw, 1980).
On heating milk (>90℃), a pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the
casein micelles occurs (Kudo, 1980; Singh & Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer,
1991; Anema et al., 1993). Little K-casein dissociates from the micelles on heat
treatment of unconcentrated milk at pH lower than maximum heat stability (pH
<6.7). Above pH 6.7, a high proportion of the x-casein, complexed with dena-
tured whey proteins, is dissociated from the casein micelles. As the milk solids
concentration is increased, the heat-induced dissociation of K-casein occurs at
progressively lower pH and the extent of dissociation increases (Singh & Crea-
mer, 1991; Anema et al., 1993).
Singh & Fox (1985, 1986) proposed that, as K-casein is the major stabilising
component of the casein micelles, the minimum in the HCT-pH profile for
unconcentrated milk (Rose, 1961) results from the premature coagulation of the
K-casein-depleted casein micelles through calcium-mediated aggregation reac-
tions. Although K-casein dissociation increases at higher pH, the heat stability
increases again due to the increase in protein charge which is sufficient to offset
the destabilisation effects of K-casein depletion. Similarly, Singh & Creamer
(1991) suggested that the low heat stability of concentrated milk over a wide pH
range (6.3-7.3) is due to the increased dissociation of K-casein at lower pH. The
heat coagulation process of concentrated milk is therefore comparable with that
existing for unconcentrated milk in the region of minimum heat stability and
several pieces of experimental evidence support this view (Muir & Sweetsur, 1978;
Singh & Creamer, 1992).
The present study clearly indicated that the K-casein-depleted micelles, formed
(-Potentials of casein micelles from heated skim milk
when milk was heated at pH 7.1, had a lower (-potential than the whey-protein-
coated micelles formed when milk was heated at pH 6.6. In concurrence with
earlier reports, the minima in the HCT-pH profile of unconcentrated milk and
the low stability of concentrated milk throughout the pH range could be
explained as being a consequence of the reduction in ¿- potential and steric stabi-
lisation due to the pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the micelles (Singh
& Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer, 1991). Alternatively, the reduction in (-
potential may arise from an increase in the heat-induced precipitation of calcium
phosphate at higher milk pH. An association of this calcium phosphate with
casein may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential.
Surprisingly, the (-potentials did not markedly increase at pH higher than that
where the minimum heat stability of milk occurs. Unless this situation is different
at high temperatures, the increase in heat stability of unconcentrated milk at pH
above 7.0 cannot be explained by an increase in the surface charge of the micelles.
As the direct cause of coagulation of the K-casein-depleted micelles is considered
to be their increased sensitivity to precipitation by calcium, the increase in stabi-
lity at higher pH may simply be a result of the reduced availability of ionic
calcium.
The results shown in Fig. 3 indicate that the heat-induced dissociation of
micellar K-casein is partially reversible on pH readjustment after heat treatment.
For the sample heated at pH 6.6, little soluble casein was noted and virtually no
effect was observed on readjusting the pH after heat treatment. In contrast, for
the samples heated at pH 7.1, the dissociated K-casein partially reassociated with
the casein micelles when the pH was lowered, with the degree of reassociation
increasing at lower pH. In addition, the level of dissociated K-casein increased if
the pH after heat treatment was raised. These results suggest that the convergence
of the (-potential-pH curves for the samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1 may be a
consequence of the reassociation of K-casein with the casein micelles when the pH
is lowered after heat treatment. As the solubility of calcium phosphate salts
increases with a reduction in pH, the convergence of the two curves could also be
explained by the resolubilisation of heat-precipitated calcium phosphate as the
pH of the system is reduced.
CONCLUSIONS
This study has demonstrated that the changes in (-potential in heated skim milk
are consistent with the present theory for the pH-dependence of the heat stability
of skim milk. Casein micelles from milk samples heated at pH 7.1 had lower č-
potentials than those from milk samples heated at pH 6.6. The (-potential of the
casein micelles did not increase at pH above 7 suggesting that the increase in the
heat stability of unconcentrated skim milk at these high pH values may be a
consequence of the decrease in calcium ion concentration rather than an increase
in protein charge. However, the reduced (-potentials could also be explained by
increased precipitation of calcium phosphate at higher pH.
A major limitation in studying the changes to casein micelles on heat treatment
is that, with the current technology, it is not possible to measure the (-potential at
the temperature of heating. Unlike the rennet treatment of milk, where the effect
of the specific cleavage of the glycomacropeptide from the micelle can be exam-
ined with limited complications from accompanying side reactions, there are
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer
several heat-induced changes occurring in the milk system that are expected to
affect the micellar (-potential (Fox, 1980; Singh, 1988; Singh & Fox, 1988; Singh
& Creamer, 1992). Many of these changes are dependent on the milk concentra-
tion and pH before heating and are at least partially reversible on the subsequent
cooling.

(-Potentials of Casein Micelles from Reconstituted Skim Milk Heated at 120℃

Skelte G. Anemaab* & Henning Klostermeyerª ªForschungszentrum für Milch und Lebensmittel Weihenstephan, Technische Universität München, D85350 Freising, Germany bPresent address: Food Science Section, New Zealand Dairy Research Institute, Private Bag 11029, Palmerston, North New Zealand (Received 20 January 1995; accepted 21 October 1995)
ABSTRACT

Laser Doppler electrophoresis was used to determine the (-potentials of casein micelles in untreated, rennet treated or heated (pH 6.6 or 7.1|120℃ for 6, 15 or 25 min) reconstituted skim milk samples as a function of pH. Complex (-poten- tial-pH profiles were observed for untreated milk samples, with local maxima at pH 5.0 and 6.5 and corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. Rennet treatment of milk reduced the micellar (-potential by approximately one-third. On heat treat- ment of the milk, the maxima and minima were either markedly reduced or elimi- nated. In addition, the casein micelles from the samples heated at pH 6.6 had higher (-potentials than those from the samples heated at pH 7.1 over the entire pH range. Low levels of K-casein were dissociated from the casein micelles on heat treatment at pH 6.6, whereas about 50% of the K-casein was rendered soluble on heat treatment at pH 7.1. This dissociation of K-casein, which was partially reversible on readjustment of the pH, may account for the observed differences in micellar (-potential between milk samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1. Copyright C 1996 Elsevier Science Limited
INTRODUCTION

The caseins of bovine milk are in the form of colloidal aggregates called micelles. Although the detailed structure of the casein micelle has not been unequivocally elucidated, several models have been proposed (Rose, 1969; Waugh, 1971; Slat- tery & Evard, 1973; Schmidt, 1980, 1982; Horne et al., 1989; Holt, 1992). These *To whom correspondence should be addressed.
S. G. Anema & H. Klostermeyer

models have been progressively refined as more information on the micelle structure has become available. Most of the experimental data to date can be explained by a porous structure composed of small units, the sub-micelles, which are held together by colloidal calcium phosphate (CCP). K-Casein is not spread uniformly through the micelle, but occupies a key position at the micelle surface (Kirchmeier, 1973; Schmidt, 1982; Walstra & Jenness, 1984; Walstra, 1990). Recently, Holt (1992) has proposed a structural representation of the casein micelle that departs from the current theory of defined sub-micelles, as the micelle sub-structure in this model consists of the caseins in a mineralised cross-linked protein gel arising from short range, but not long range order.

The casein micelle constitutes a colloidal system of remarkable stability, capable of withstanding the severe treatments that are commonly associated with the modern commercial processing of milk and dairy products. In most cases, hydrophobic colloids are stabilised by electrostatic repulsive forces between elec- trical double layers of the particles and the long range van der Waals' attractive forces, as has been described by the classical Deryagin-Landau-Verwey-Over- beek or DLVO theory (Verwey & Overbeek, 1948). There have been many attempts to use the DLVO theory to describe the stability of casein micelles (Green & Crutchfield, 1971; Green, 1973; Pearce, 1976); however, the limitations of this approach have been discussed by Payens (1979) and Schmidt (1982).

The importance of K-casein in maintaining casein micelle stability has been recognised for a long time. This protein is thought to be associated with the micelles in such a way that the hydrophilic negatively-charged macropeptide region projects into the solvent as flexible hairs (Walstra, 1979, 1990; Walstra & Jenness, 1984). A surface layer of this type would provide stabilisation through electrostatic repulsion between the charged casein micelles as in the DLVO mechanism, as well as steric stabilisation through entropic repulsions at close range due to the presence of the macropeptide hairs (Walstra, 1990).

The surface charge of colloids is often estimated by the (-potential which can be derived from the electrophoretic mobility of the particles. However, the quantitative calculation of (-potentials from electrophoretic mobilities for casein micelles is complicated by the fact that the nature of the electrical double layer is unknown, the micelle surface is diffuse and the micelle structure is porous and highly hydrated (Payens, 1979). Despite this limitation, the measurement of (- potentials should yield information on the nature of the outer (shear) layer of the casein micelle as changes in the chemical or physical characteristics of this surface during the treatment of milk should be apparent from the changes to the elec- trophoretic mobility and therefore the (-potential.

The electrophoretic mobility and (-potential of natural and rennet-treated casein micelles under a variety of conditions have been reported (Green & Crutchfield, 1971; Pearce, 1976; Darling & Dickson, 1979a, b; Dalgleish, 1984). In all cases, the action of rennet reduced the {-potential of the micelles to about half of the original value. The marked reduction in the (-potential on the rennet treatment of casein micelles led Green & Crutchfield (1971) to the conclusion that casein micelle stability was entirely a consequence of electrostatic repulsions; however, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Payens (1979) suggested that the magnitude of the (-potential as well as some important stability characteristics of both native and rennet-treated casein micelles were not consistent with a colloidal system stabilised by electrostatic interactions alone.
In contrast to the numerous studies on the changes in (-potential between
(-Potentials of casein micelles from heated skim milk

native and rennet-treated casein micelles, the effect of heat treatment on the (- potential of the micelles has received little attention. Numerous reactions occur when milk is heated and many are likely to have an influence on the micellar (- potential (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988; Singh & Fox, 1988; Singh & Creamer, 1992). In contrast to what may be expected, Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) reported negligible changes to the (-potential of casein micelles on heating milk to the coagulation point. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed a complex relationship between the (-potential and pH for casein micelles heated in the presence of whey proteins; however, these effects could not be related to changes in the corresponding heat stability curves.

This communication reports the results of a study on the effect of the heat treatment of skim milk reconstituted to 10 and 25% total solids (TS) on the electrophoretic mobility and thereby the calculated (-potential of casein micelles. The {-potentials of micelles from untreated and rennet-treated milk samples were compared.
MATERIALS AND METHODS
Milk supply

Reconstituted skim milk was used in all experiments as this avoided variations in milk supply and allowed milk of the required total solids to be prepared. Experi- mental reconstituted skim milk samples of 10 and 25% TS were prepared by mixing the appropriate quantity of low heat skim milk powder (whey protein nitrogen index >6; Sanderson, 1970) with purified water and allowing the mixture to equilibrate at ambient temperature (approximately 20℃) for 2 h.
Dissociation and reassociation behaviour of K-casein
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk

Milk samples (10% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1 by the slow addition of 1 M HCI or 1 M NaOH to well-stirred solutions. Sub-samples (6 mL) in glass tubes were heated at 120°℃ for 6 min in a thermostatically-controlled oil bath, then cooled by immersion into cold water. After heat treatment, the pH was readjusted to values in the range 5.0 to 8.0 with 1 M HCI or 1 M NaOH and the samples were equilibrated for 2 h.
Ultracentrifugation and gel electrophoresis

The heated, pH-adjusted milk samples were centrifuged at 88,000 g for 60 min at 25°C in a Beckman L8-80M ultracentrifuge and the associated nVT90 rotor (Beckman Instruments Inc., Palo Alto, CA, USA). The protein components in the ultracentrifugal supernatants were separated and identified by sodium dode- cyl sulphate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (SDS-PAGE), using the mini Protean II equipment (Bio-Rad Laboratories, Richmond, CA, USA) and an experimental method similar to that described by Laemmli (1970). After staining (Coomassie Blue R250) and destaining procedures, the band intensities of the major protein components were determined using a Molecular Dynamics Model P.D. Computing Densitometer (Molecular Dynamics, Sunnyvale, CA, USA) and the associated Imagequant integration software.

Measurement of (-potential and particle size
Adjustment of pH and heat treatment of milk

Milk samples (10 and 25% TS) were adjusted to pH 6.6 or 7.1, heated and cooled as described above. For the final experiments, heating times of 25 min (10% TS samples) or 15 min (25% TS samples) were used. The concentrated milk sample at pH 7.1, which had partially coagulated on heat treatment, was centrifuged at 3000 rev/min in a bench centrifuge (Sigma 3E) to remove the small amount of coagulated material and the supernatant milk sample was used for (-potential measurements.
Rennet treatment of milk

Rennet solution was prepared by dissolving 0.25 g rennet powder (Hauser rennet powder, Josef Hauser, Ottmaishausen, Germany) in 50 mL water before filtration through a 0.1 um pore size cellulose nitrate filter. Freshly prepared rennet solu- tion was added to 10% TS skim milk at room temperature.
Buffers

Synthetic milk ultrafiltrate (SMUF buffer) was prepared by the method of Jenness & Koops (1962). Immediately prior to use, samples of the SMUF buffer were adjusted to pH 4.75 to 8.0 using 1 M HCI or 1 M KOH. Ca2+-imidazole buffer was prepared from 20 mM imidazole, 50 mM NaCl and 5 mM CaCl2. The pH was adjusted to 6.0 to 7.5 by the addition of 1 M HC1. All buffers were filtered through 0.25 um pore size cellulose nitrate filters before use.
Electrophoretic mobility and (-potential determination

The electrophoretic mobilities and hence the calculated (-potentials of casein micelles were determined using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 instrument, the associated Malvern Multi-8 64 channel correlator and the AZ4 standard electrophoresis cell which incorporates a 4 mm diameter quartz capillary (Malvern Instruments Ltd, Malvern, Worcs., UK). The temperature of the electrophoresis cell was maintained at 30°℃ by a water jacket which was temperature controlled by the Peltier system associated with the electrophoresis cell. Monitoring of temperature indicated that control was better than +0.5℃. An applied voltage of 80 V (corresponding to a sensed voltage of approximately 60 V across the capillary, i.e. approximately 12 V/ cm) and a modulation frequency of 250 Hz were used in all experiments.

The SMUF and Ca2+-imidazole buffers were highly conducting, which resul- ted in sample heating if voltages were applied for long periods. This was over- come by using duty cycle mode in which the voltage was switched off for short periods between each voltage pulse to allow generated heat to dissipate. A duty cycle of 60% (a voltage pulse of 30 ms followed by an off-time of 20 ms) was used in all experiments. Electrode polarisation was avoided by reversing the direction of the applied field every 2 Hz.

Samples for {-potential measurement were prepared by suspending typically 50 uL of 10% TS milk or 20 uL of 25% TS milk in 15 mL of the appropriate buffer; however, for buffers in the pH range 5.25 to 6.0, higher milk concentrations, up to 200 AL of 10% TS milk in 15 mL of buffer, were required to give samples that were sufficiently turbid. Milk samples dispersed in the appropriate buffer were allowed to equilibrate for 15 min before (-potential determination. Each sample was measured in triplicate. The error in the (-potential determinations, determined by repeatedly

measuring the (-potential of unheated casein micelles in SMUF or Ca2+-imidazole buffer, was found to be consistently better than +0.5 mV.
Casein micelle size measurements

Particle sizes in untreated and heated milk (10% TS samples at pH 6.6 or 7.1 only) were measured in suspensions by adding 25 uL of milk to 15 mL of Ca2+_ imidazole buffer at pH 7.0. Measurements of the average diameters were made using a Malvern Zetasizer 3 in photon correlation mode, with the correlation functions measured at a scattering angle of 90° only. The correlation functions were analysed by the method of cumulants to give average diffusion coefficients from which the average hydrodynamic diameters and polydispersity of the parti- cles were calculated using Stokes' law. Each sample was measured five times and the average size and polydispersity determined.
All experiments reported above were repeated on at least two occasions with similar results.

The calculated ¿- potentials of casein micelles from unheated milk samples dispersed in SMUF buffer and filtered through 0.8 um pore size filters were, within error, indistinguishable from those of unfiltered samples. Dalgleish (1984) reported that, if fresh milk was skimmed by centrifugation and no other measures were taken to remove fat, two peaks corresponding to the (-potentials of casein micelles and fat globules were observed. It is possible that in these experiments, where reconstituted skim milk was used, the fat globules remaining in the skim milk powder were well homogenised so that casein micelle material formed a synthetic fat globule membrane. Dalgleish (1984) established that particles from homo- genised milk had (-potentials very similar to those of native casein micelles. All further (-potential determinations were on unfiltered milk suspensions as it was possible that filtration may remove some of the larger particles formed during the heat treatment of milk and therefore influence the calculated ¿- potential. Particles from heated milk samples also tended to adsorb to the cellulose nitrate filters which made the preparation of suitably concentrated suspensions difficult.
Comparison of ¿- potentials of casein micelles from untreated and rennet-treated skim milk

The (-potentials for native casein micelles, measured in SMUF buffer, ranged from about -20 to -13 mV over the pH range 8.0 to 4.75 (Fig. 1). The relation- ship between pH and (-potential for casein micelles showed local maxima at pH 5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5. When Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used as the suspending medium, the calculated (-potentials were markedly lower than the values found when using SMUF buffer (Fig. 1).

The rennet treatment of the milk reduced the (-potential of the casein micelles to about two-thirds of the original value in both buffer systems. As with the native casein micelles, the apparent (-potentials were markedly lower when the Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used instead of the SMUF buffer (Fig. 1). Rennet solution was added to milk at low concentration so that the enzymatic reaction lasted for about 100 min. To avoid the formation of large particles, which can cause problems with anomalous light scattering, the rennet-treated milk was dispersed in the buffers before the completion of the enzymatic reaction (i.e. after about 50 min).
The (-potentials of casein micelles from heat-treated skim milk

The (-potential-pH profiles for casein micelles from the heated skim milk samples, in comparison with unheated milk, are shown in Fig. 2. The maximum and minimum observed at high pH in the unheated milk were less pronounced in the samples heated at pH 6.6.

For both the 10 and 25% TS milk concentrations at any particular pH, the (- potentials of the micelles from the milk samples heated at pH 6.6 were higher than those for the corresponding samples heated at pH 7.1 in both buffer systems.

The (-potentials were also similar to those obtained by Dalgleish (1984), although markedly higher than the results Banon & Hardy (1992); these latter two studies also used laser Doppler electrophoresis techniques. The (-potential values for casein micelles reported here were almost twice as high as those determined by electro- osmosis techniques (Payens, 1966; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).

The marked reduction in micellar (-potential when the suspending medium was changed from SMUF to Ca2+-imidazole buffer (Fig. 1 and Fig. 2) may have been a reflection of the difference in Ca2+ activity between the two buffer systems, although factors such as differences in buffer viscosity or the presence of ions such as phosphate may have also contributed to this disparity. Both Pearce (1976) and Dalgleish (1984) showed that increasing Ca2+ concentration caused a considerable decrease in the (-potential of native and rennet-treated casein micelles.

Considering only the protein part of casein micelles, a steady increase in (- potential with increasing pH would be expected (Shaw, 1980). However, the observed relationship between the (-potential of native casein micelles from milk dispersed in SMUF buffer and pH is considerably more complex, as local maxima were observed at pH 5.0 and 6.5 with corresponding minima at pH 5.5 and 7.5 (Fig. 1). Overall, the (-potential-pH profile shown in Fig. 1 is similar to that reported by Schmidt & Poll (1986) for casein micelles heated in the absence of whey proteins; however, the entire curve is transposed by about 10 mV to higher (-potential. In addition, Schmidt & Poll (1986) did not observe the maxi- mum at pH 6.5 and the minimum at pH 7.5 unless whey proteins were present during heating of the casein micelles. Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Banon & Hardy (1992) reported an almost linear decrease in the (-potential of casein micelles with decreasing pH when milk ultrafiltrate was used as the dispersion medium.

The complete solubilisation of CCP at pH 5.3 (Van Hooydonk et al., 1986; Dalgleish & Law, 1989) may be responsible for the maximum and minimum in the (-potential-pH profile at pH 5.0 and 5.5, respectively (Walstra, 1990). Alter- natively, these extremes may arise from changes in the surface charge character- istics of the casein micelle as a consequence of the increased adsorption of ionic calcium to protein-bound phosphate groups at pH in the range 5.3 to 5.6 (Crea- mer, 1985; Schmidt & Poll, 1986).

As no (-potential maximum at pH 6.5 or minimum at pH 7.5 were observed when Ca2+-imidazole buffer was used, these may be a consequence of pH- dependent changes in the properties of the SMUF buffer. The addition of milk to SMUF buffer during sample preparation partially inhibited the precipitation of calcium phosphate from these buffers at high pH (>7.0). This indicated that the calcium phosphate may preferentially adsorb to the casein micelles. This asso- ciation may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential, and hence account for the minimum at pH 7.5.

The (-potential at pH 4.75 was markedly higher than zero (Fig. 1). This contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) and Schmidt & Poll (1986) who reported a (-potential of zero at the isoelectric pH of casein (pH 4.6). Due to the complete solubilisation of the CCP, the calcium and phosphate concentrations, the calcium ion activity and the ionic strength of natural milk
