serum at pH 4.75 would be considerably higher than in the SMUF buffer used in these experiments, which simulates milk serum at pH 6.6. It is possible that these differences result in a higher -potential of the casein micelles in the SMUF buffer systems at low pH.

The heat treatment of milk at high temperatures results in many physical and chemical changes to the milk system that may influence the casein micelle (- potential. These changes include precipitation of calcium phosphate, depho- sphorylation of casein, association of heat-denatured whey proteins with the casein micelles and the dissociation of micellar casein (Fox, 1981; Singh, 1988; Singh & Creamer, 1992). The results shown in Fig. 2 demonstrate that heat treatment of the skim milk affected the (-potential-pH profile of the casein micelles. In all cases, the {-potentials of the casein micelles from the milk samples heated at pH 6.6 were higher than in samples adjusted to pH 7.1, although the differences were small at pH below 6.0 due to the convergence of the curves at low pH. This contrasts with the results of Darling & Dickson (1979a, b) who reported no significant effect of the heat treatment of milk up to the coagulation point. The comparison is complicated by the fact that they heated milk samples only at pH close to that naturally observed and did not take the pH change incurred by heating into account. Schmidt & Poll (1986) showed that the heat treatment of casein micelle dispersions in the presence of whey proteins increased the (-potential in the pH range 6.6 to 6.9 but reduced it at higher pH.

The particle size results given in Table 1 demonstrate that differences in micelle size as a consequence of the heat treatments of 10% TS milk samples could not account for the observed differences in (-potential between pH 6.6 and 7.1. It should be noted that the electrophoretic mobility, and therefore the derived (- potentials of non-conducting particles, as derived from the Smoluchowski equa- tion, should be independent of their size and shape (Shaw, 1980).

On heating milk (>90℃), a pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the casein micelles occurs (Kudo, 1980; Singh & Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer, 1991; Anema et al., 1993). Little K-casein dissociates from the micelles on heat treatment of unconcentrated milk at pH lower than maximum heat stability (pH <6.7). Above pH 6.7, a high proportion of the x-casein, complexed with dena- tured whey proteins, is dissociated from the casein micelles. As the milk solids concentration is increased, the heat-induced dissociation of K-casein occurs at progressively lower pH and the extent of dissociation increases (Singh & Crea- mer, 1991; Anema et al., 1993).

Singh & Fox (1985, 1986) proposed that, as K-casein is the major stabilising component of the casein micelles, the minimum in the HCT-pH profile for unconcentrated milk (Rose, 1961) results from the premature coagulation of the K-casein-depleted casein micelles through calcium-mediated aggregation reac- tions. Although K-casein dissociation increases at higher pH, the heat stability increases again due to the increase in protein charge which is sufficient to offset the destabilisation effects of K-casein depletion. Similarly, Singh & Creamer (1991) suggested that the low heat stability of concentrated milk over a wide pH range (6.3-7.3) is due to the increased dissociation of K-casein at lower pH. The heat coagulation process of concentrated milk is therefore comparable with that existing for unconcentrated milk in the region of minimum heat stability and several pieces of experimental evidence support this view (Muir & Sweetsur, 1978; Singh & Creamer, 1992).
The present study clearly indicated that the K-casein-depleted micelles, formed
(-Potentials of casein micelles from heated skim milk

when milk was heated at pH 7.1, had a lower (-potential than the whey-protein- coated micelles formed when milk was heated at pH 6.6. In concurrence with earlier reports, the minima in the HCT-pH profile of unconcentrated milk and the low stability of concentrated milk throughout the pH range could be explained as being a consequence of the reduction in ¿- potential and steric stabi- lisation due to the pH-dependent dissociation of K-casein from the micelles (Singh & Fox, 1985, 1986; Singh & Creamer, 1991). Alternatively, the reduction in (- potential may arise from an increase in the heat-induced precipitation of calcium phosphate at higher milk pH. An association of this calcium phosphate with casein may shield the negative charges on the micelles, reducing the (-potential. Surprisingly, the (-potentials did not markedly increase at pH higher than that where the minimum heat stability of milk occurs. Unless this situation is different at high temperatures, the increase in heat stability of unconcentrated milk at pH above 7.0 cannot be explained by an increase in the surface charge of the micelles. As the direct cause of coagulation of the K-casein-depleted micelles is considered to be their increased sensitivity to precipitation by calcium, the increase in stabi- lity at higher pH may simply be a result of the reduced availability of ionic calcium.

The results shown in Fig. 3 indicate that the heat-induced dissociation of micellar K-casein is partially reversible on pH readjustment after heat treatment. For the sample heated at pH 6.6, little soluble casein was noted and virtually no effect was observed on readjusting the pH after heat treatment. In contrast, for the samples heated at pH 7.1, the dissociated K-casein partially reassociated with the casein micelles when the pH was lowered, with the degree of reassociation increasing at lower pH. In addition, the level of dissociated K-casein increased if the pH after heat treatment was raised. These results suggest that the convergence of the (-potential-pH curves for the samples heated at pH 6.6 and 7.1 may be a consequence of the reassociation of K-casein with the casein micelles when the pH is lowered after heat treatment. As the solubility of calcium phosphate salts increases with a reduction in pH, the convergence of the two curves could also be explained by the resolubilisation of heat-precipitated calcium phosphate as the pH of the system is reduced.
CONCLUSIONS

This study has demonstrated that the changes in (-potential in heated skim milk are consistent with the present theory for the pH-dependence of the heat stability of skim milk. Casein micelles from milk samples heated at pH 7.1 had lower č- potentials than those from milk samples heated at pH 6.6. The (-potential of the casein micelles did not increase at pH above 7 suggesting that the increase in the heat stability of unconcentrated skim milk at these high pH values may be a consequence of the decrease in calcium ion concentration rather than an increase in protein charge. However, the reduced (-potentials could also be explained by increased precipitation of calcium phosphate at higher pH.

A major limitation in studying the changes to casein micelles on heat treatment is that, with the current technology, it is not possible to measure the (-potential at the temperature of heating. Unlike the rennet treatment of milk, where the effect of the specific cleavage of the glycomacropeptide from the micelle can be exam- ined with limited complications from accompanying side reactions, there are
